<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: BUENA PARK; KNOTT'S IS ROOT OF ALL BOYSENBERRIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 All of those plump, juicy, dark red boysenberries in the world can be traced 
to their roots in Knott's Berry Farm. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 60 years ago, theme park founder and farmer Walter Knott was always 
looking for crops he could grow better than other farmers, said Patsy Marshall, 
Knott's historian. 
</P>
<P>
 And the boysenberry, a cross between a loganberry, red raspberry and 
blackberry, became Knott's Berry Farm's claim to fame -- in pies, jams and 
jellies. 
</P>
<P>
 Knott became associated with the boysenberry back in 1932 after Rudolph 
Boysen, who was parks superintendent for Anaheim, had experimented with a new 
type of berry. 
</P>
<P>
 But the berries weren't growing well and were dying on the vine, Marshall 
said. Knott was intrigued with the new strain of berry and offered to take in 
the scraggly plants, nursing them back to health, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 As a tribute to the berry's originator, Knott named it after Boysen. 
</P>
<P>
 Boysenberries are the largest of all berries, averaging 1 1/2 to 2 inches in 
length and 1 inch in diameter. DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
