CORPORATE SNAPSHOT: SUMMA INDUSTRIES, FULLERTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nature of business: Designs and manufactures industrial equipment 
</P>
<P>
 Total employees: 227 
</P>
<P>
 In Orange County: 67 
</P>
<P>
 Stock listing in The Times: On Nasdaq "Summa" 
</P>
<P>
 Ticker symbol: "SUIN" 
</P>
<P>
 Friday's stock close: $6.25 
</P>
<P>
 One-week change: Down $0.25 
</P>
<P>
 Analyst review: "Summa Industries used to be called Morehouse Industries. It 
changed its name and offered a one-for-four reverse stock split last month. 
Things were stagnant for them for a while, with sales slow and costs creeping 
up. But James Swartwout, the CEO, has developed a strategy to improve the top 
line through acquisitions. Summa's principal business used to be large, 
industrial mixing machines, but it acquired other niche businesses, including 
one that manufactures water cannons for fireboats and another company that 
makes plastic grid conveyor belts used in food processing plants. The companies 
he acquired were usually the only ones making a particular product or by far 
the dominant player. Swartwout knows how to run a company from a financial 
standpoint and he will be working to get some growth out ot these 
divisions."--Jim Liuzzi, analyst, Cruttenden & Co., Irvine 
</P>
