<HEADLINE>
<P>
NFL PLAYOFFS / NOTES; AFC PLAYOFFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE SPRINGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday's game established AFC playoff records for penalties by one team and 
for two teams combined.In both cases, the Raiders broke their own records. 
</P>
<P>
 Their 17 penalties Sunday were three more than the previous record set by the 
Oakland Raiders during a 1980 game against Houston. The record of 14 was tied a 
year later by San Francisco in an NFC playoff game against the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
 Together, the Raiders and Broncos had 27 penalties, easily breaking the record 
of 22 set in three different games -- the same Raider-Oiler game, the same 
49er-Giant game and a game between Houston and Cleveland in 1988. STEVE 
SPRINGER 
</P>
