<HEADLINE>
<P>
NFL PLAYOFFS / NOTES; AFC PLAYOFFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It has been a few days, but Buddy Ryan says he has no regrets about The Punch. 
</P>
<P>
 The Houston Oilers' defensive coordinator told the Philadelphia Inquirer that 
the blow to offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride on Jan. 2 during the Oilers' 
victory over the New York Jets served its purpose. 
</P>
<P>
 "I guarantee you won't see him making calls like that again," Ryan said. 
</P>
<P>
 Ryan hit Gilbride in the face after an Oiler offensive play called about 30 
seconds before halftime resulted in a sack and led to a Jet field-goal attempt. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a third-down offense, not a pro offense," Ryan said in the interview 
conducted Tuesday in Houston. "And he has no business coaching the pros. He 
should be selling insurance." 
</P>
<P>
 Ryan, 59, says Gilbride had it coming. 
</P>
<P>
 "Everybody thinks that it's all my fault, and they keep showing that on TV," 
Ryan said. " . . . He is the one who made the move. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know what I said. I might have called him a high school coach. 
Something like that. He was cussing me and coming at me." 
</P>
